{"block1":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"arthritis-diagnosis\"  >Arthritis<\/a> has always affected people, and it&rsquo;s not choosy about&nbsp;whom it affects. Arthritis by definition is inflammation of the joint, which can cause stiffness and pain. Arthritis can be frustrating and disabling if left untreated, and can affect your whole lifestyle.&nbsp; Finding out you have arthritis can be upsetting, and raises lots of questions, such as:&nbsp;how did I get arthritis?<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">You may have injured your joint years ago and, for some reason,&nbsp;it never healed properly.&nbsp; While it may have&nbsp;seemed fine at the time,&nbsp;hidden in there was undetected damage to the joint which ultimately lead to arthritis.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img src=\"\/images\/photo-of-a-man-holding-his-knee.jpg\" class=\"img_left \" alt=\"photo of a man holding his knee\" style=\"float: left; padding: 8px; padding-left: 0;\" \/><\/h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">It is possible that&nbsp;you overused the joint, by using it constantly, either at work or through physical activity, or by being overweight.&nbsp; Constant pressure can result from sitting long periods of time at work; standing for long periods also puts pressure on the joint.&nbsp;&nbsp; Baseball pitchers and dancers are at risk for arthritis because of their constant use of the joints.&nbsp; Being overweight puts pressure on the hips, knees, and ankles, and can also cause&nbsp;arthritis.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">You may have an auto immune disorder that caused your arthritis.&nbsp; An auto immune disorder causes the immune system to attack the joint and damage it.&nbsp; White blood cells then form around the tissue and cartilage in the joint, attacking the health of the joint.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><img src=\"\/images\/photo-of-a-woman-with-rheumatoid-arthritis.jpg\" class=\"img_right \" alt=\"photo of a woman with rheumatoid arthritis\" style=\"float: right; padding: 8px; padding-right: 0;\" \/><\/h4>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Age is certainly a factor for&nbsp;arthritis sufferers.&nbsp; Arthritis usually shows up around age 50 or older.&nbsp; However, adolescents can have arthritis, especially rheumatoid arthritis, but most adolescents affected by arthritis have&nbsp;a 75% remission by age 16.&nbsp; Women are more susceptible to some types of arthritis because of childbearing.&nbsp; As we get older, the&nbsp;body slows down, no longer providing the nutrients it needs to keep itself healthy.&nbsp; Women also undergo hormonal changes that can affect the natural balance of the body.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Genetics also play a role in&nbsp;arthritis.&nbsp; If your parents were arthritis sufferers, there&#39;s&nbsp;a good chance that you inherited it from them.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">There are more than a hundred different types of arthritis known today.&nbsp; The questions of how, what, and why are always waiting&nbsp;to be answered. However,&nbsp;with there being so many types of arthritis, you may not always be able to find out the cause.&nbsp; Researchers are still looking for causes for some types of arthritis.&nbsp; The two most common types of arthritis today affect one in every five adults.&nbsp; These types are osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">While the causes listed above may answer the &quot;how?&quot; and &quot;why?&quot;, the &quot;what?&quot;&nbsp;is up to you.&nbsp; Only you can choose &quot;what&quot; you are going to do.&nbsp; <a href=\"http:\/\/jointreport.net\/joint-information\/how-arthritis-can-be-treated\/\"  >Arthritis symptoms are manageable<\/a>.&nbsp; Arthritis doesn&rsquo;t have to hinder your lifestyle.&nbsp; Talk with your doctor and&nbsp;find the best treatment plan for your symptoms to allow you to continue&nbsp;a good-quality lifestyle.<\/p>\r\n"}